<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-691-333  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 691 333.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 17 1990 v7 n50 p141(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NCR chief sends mixed messages about ATandamp;T bid. (NCR Corp. chairmanCharles Exley)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brennan, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Acquisitions and mergers)NCR Corp. (Acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    T; NCR.andO;Topic:     AcquisitionBusiness PlanningComputer industryExecutive.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   NCR's sales plateau. (graph)Person:    Exley, Charles E., Jr. (Planning).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Laura BrennanandM;Charles Exley, NCR Corp.'s chairman, has delighted observers in the last twoweeks with down-to-earth rhetoric lambasting ATandamp;T's hostile attempt to &quot;reachout and grab&quot; his company.andM;But last week, as NCR directors rejected ATandamp;T's $6.12 billion offer and filedsuit against the company, analysts began to wonder whether Exley doth protesttoo much.andM;The chairman has already softened his stance on resigning if an ATandamp;T proxyfight succeeds, saying he would participate in a smooth executive transition.andM;Furthermore, after ATandamp;T made its $90-per-share bid Dec.andP;  2, Exley counteredwith a price of $125 per share, but defended the move as nothing more than afair assessment of NCR's stock.andP;  NCR officials said they rejected ATandamp;T'soffer because it was &quot;grossly inadequate.&quot;andM;Despite Exley's claim that NCR is not holding out for more money, industryleaders believe that to be the case.andM;&quot;If [ATandamp;T] had gone in at $250 a share, they wouldn't have been consideredhostile,&quot; said Scott McNealy, president and CEO of Sun Microsystems Inc., inMountain View, Calif.andM;For all his good intentions, Exley's words and actions seem contradictory.andO;Analysts believe he would not have met with ATandamp;T officials last month had henot been interested in their offer.andM;&quot;When Exley met with ATandamp;T, he opened a Pandora's box,&quot; said George Colony,president of Forrester Research Inc., a market-research firm in Cambridge,Mass.andP;  &quot;Now, it's done.andP;  I don't know if ATandamp;T will get them, but NCR will besold.&quot;andM;Still, as Exley confirmed that potential white knights have approached NCR,he repeated last week that the Dayton, Ohio, company wants to be left aloneto pursue its new product strategy.andM;After several quarters of flat revenue growth (see chart, Page 141), NCRinjected life into its product line this fall by announcing plans toeliminate proprietary systems in favor of Intel-based computers.andM;The outcome of that strategy, like Exley's mixed messages, is neither blacknor white, according to analysts.andM;First, the plan won't pay off until 1992, analysts say.andP;  In the meantime, NCRfaces sluggish sales in its traditionally strong markets: banking and retail.andM;NCR also faces a risk that customers of its proprietary systems may embracethe &quot;open systems&quot; strategy, but buy equipment from other companies, saidBarry Bosak, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham andamp; Co., an investmentfirm in New York.andM;&quot;NCR has lost nothing by pursuing this strategy, but at this point, I don'tknow if it will succeed.andP;  They believe it will work,&quot; said Sanjiv Hingorani,vice president of Salomon Brothers Inc., an investment firm in New York.andM;If the strategy fails, ATandamp;T's bid -- in retrospect -- might not seem quite sohostile, analysts said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>